<br>
Anyway, not mad or a rant, just wanted people to realize that the LotR books can be read/interpreted a ton of different ways.  As such, for such a book, i think the movie was done really well.  Now, yes, I know what you're thinking, &quot;But Mike, you said you didn't like the books.&quot;  And well... I really didn't.  Now bear with me a moment as I explain.<br>
<br>
You see, when I read a novel, I like to be part of the novel.  I like to feel the sweat pouring off of me when I'm wandering through the wasteland, I like to hear the drums beating of the army marching to it's last stand, I like to laugh and dance at the ball.  For me, Tolkeen didn't do this.  Sure I was there, but it was being told to me.  I didn't get to experience it.  I got to read about it in the Morning Paper.<br>
<br>
As such, I felt separated from the story.  I felt like I wasn't really a part of the adventure.  I could close the book, and open it 3 months later, and wouldn't have to worry that the &quot;bad guys&quot; would win without me reading the book.  That's really why I didn't like Tolkeen.  Other books I've read, and series that I've watched, I had to keep reading or watching because I was there.  If I stopped, the hero's, heroines, and protagonists would fail without me helping in any little way I could.<br>
<br>
Tolkeen had vision, he was willing to be a pioneer in a field when High Fantasy had previously been novels like &quot;Seven Samurai&quot;, &quot;Don Quixote&quot;, &quot;The Oddesy&quot;, &quot;The Illiad,&quot; and the like.  He created a world out of nothing more than the willpower of his immagination.  He drew from legends, myths, fables, fairy tales, bardic stores, and lore to weave an entirely new world.<br>
<br>
But he weaved the world in such a way that I wasn't part of it.<br>
<br>
When I read Jordan's &quot;Wheel of Time,&quot; I feel like I'm with them... at every dance, at every council meeting, at every fight, giving what courage, what dignity, what honor I can to aid them.  When I was reading Donaldson, I felt this same way.  When I read Lovecraft, I was right there, as confused, as frighted, but as desiring as the protagonists.<br>
<br>
My point is Tolkeen writes a good book.  But, for me, it's still dry becuase he wrote it in such a way that it's not an epic story, but an epic history text.  A text of stories that have already occured, have come to a conclusion, and that doesn't really need me around.<br>
<br>
